description: Naramachi Museum exhibits various tools, signboards and other items used in the Edo and Meiji Periods. The owner of this museum is Mr. Tetsuro Minami, whose ancestor started mosquito net manufacturing business in 1907 in Naramachi. Many of the exhibited items were found in the old storehouse of his family or in their neighbors’ and friends’ houses. He and his father collected them with great care and efforts. They have altered part of their private residence to exhibit their collections. The museum is open to the public for free.

name: Kasuga Wakamiya Ommatsuri
ranking_subcategory: #134 of 271 things to do in Nara
subcategory_ranking: #134 of 271 things to do in Nara
ranking: #134 of 271 things to do in Nara
description: The Kasuga Wakamiya Ommatsuri is an annual spring festival and a nationally-designated Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property. It is held for several days around December 17th at Wakamiya Shrine, a subordinate shrine to Kasuga Grand Shrine. The festival began in 1136 as a prayer by Fujiwara no Tadamichi for a large harvest, and has been honored every year since, without exception. At midnight on the 17th, the senkou-no-gi (ceremony of the Emperor's departure) begins. The sacred palanquin of Wakamiya Shrine is carried from the main building to its provisional housing, and in keeping with its traditionally secret status, no photography is permitted and flashlights are also prohibited. The result is a solemn, mysterious atmosphere in the dark of the night. During the day, mannerisms and styles from the Heian to the Edo period can be seen in the magnificent o-watari-shiki (ceremony of passage) parade.
